ce:section.ce:para:
Considering the significantly higher PL intensity of the B-C-dots/PMMA and B-C-dots/PS based LSCs compared to B-C-dots/PVP and B-C-dots/PVA based LSCs, and to eliminate the effect of the polymer solvent on the B-C-dots, the device performances of B-C-dots/PMMA and B-C-dots/PS based LSCs were further measured by irradiating the surface of the LSCs under natural sunlight and simulated sunlight. The thickness of the LSCs is about 5 mm. Therefore, to evaluate their PV performance, a silicon solar cell with an active area of 38 × 5 mm2 was coupled to one edge of the LSCs. The relationship between optical transmission distance and optical efficiency for the both types of LSCs was studied and the relevant schematic diagram is exhibited in Fig. 4
                        a. During the measurement, the light illuminate area was confined to 10 × 1 cm2, while the rest was shielded with light barriers. The optical transmission distance in the device was adjusted by modifying the illumination region. Fig. S6 shows the photocurrent density–voltage (J-V) curves of the LSCs as the optical transmission distance increased under 40 mW/cm2 simulated sunlight illumination. It is evident that with the optical distance increases, the JLSC decreases. In the LSCs, the efficiency of the device is mainly affected by the following points (Fig,4a): (1) limited by the absorption spectrum of fluorescent materials, only part of the incident light energy is absorbed by fluorescent materials; (2) due to the PL QY <100 %, the absorbed sunlight cannot be completely converted into fluorescence; (3) caused by the overlap of the absorption and emission spectra of fluorescent materials, the emitted photons are reabsorbed during photons transmission, resulting in energy loss. Therefore, the efficiency decreases with increasing transmission distance mainly due to the reabsorption loss. To better illustrate the impact of optical transmission distance on device performance, the ηopt of the device under various optical transmission distance was calculated. As displayed in Fig. 4b, the ηopt of both types of LSCs shows gradually reduce with prolonged optical distance, which is mainly due to the scattering losses during the transportation of emitted light from C-dots. Further, we measured the optical efficiency of the LSCs (10 × 10 × 0.5 cm3) under natural sunlight irradiation (65–70 mW/cm2). Fig. 4c,d shows the typical J-V curves of the B-C-dots/PMMA and B-C-dots/PS based LSCs-solar cell systems and the solar cell under the same sunlight illumination. For the B-C-dots/PMMA based LSC (Fig. 4c), the JLSC, VOC and PCE are 5.71 mA/cm2, 0.52 V and 3.16 %, respectively, under 68 mW/cm2 natural sunlight illumination. When the solar cell was directly illuminated under the same sunlight illumination, the JSC, VOC and PCE are 24.26 mA/cm2, 0.58 V and 14.12 %, respectively. The corresponding ηopt is 4.71 % according to Eq. (2). Similarly, for the B-C-dots/PS based LSC (Fig. 4d), under 69 mW/cm2 natural sunlight illumination, the JLSC, VOC and PCE are 6.76 mA/cm2, 0.52 V and 3.77 %, respectively. The solar cell obtained JSC, VOC and PCE of 24.69 mA/cm2, 0.58 V and 14.18 %, respectively, under directly natural sunlight illumination (69 mW/cm2). And ηopt of this LSC is 5.48 %, which is comparable with the recent reports (Table 2
                        ). Comparing the two types of LSCs, which contained the same amounts of B-C-dots and were processed with the same polymer solvent, the different property of the LSCs is primarily related to the performance of the polymer (e.g. refractive index, which determines the total reflection efficiency). To investigate the effect of the refractive index on device performance, we further calculated the ηopt of the LSC under different refractive index using the same absorption and fluorescence spectra (Fig. S7a) by the method reported in previous literature (Supporting Information) [37,38]. As shown in Fig. S7b, the ηopt of the LSCs decreases with the increase of the size of the LSCs due to the reabsorption energy loss, which is consistent with the experimental results (Fig. 4b). Compare with the different refractive index, the ηopt is increased with the refractive index increases. Thus, except for the intrinsic properties of the fluorescent materials, the selection of suitable polymers (e.g. high refractive index and high transparency) also plays an important role in improving the performance of the device.
